          "body": "Moses's opening question to Pharaoh is the chapter's sharpest pastoral probe: 'How long will you refuse to humble yourself before Me?' (10:3). The Hebrew root for 'humble' (anah) carries the sense of being brought low, of yielding one's own will to a greater authority. What Pharaoh refuses is not merely political capitulation — it is the posture of a creature before his Creator. The announced consequence is the locust (10:4-6), described in terms unprecedented in human memory ('neither your fathers nor your grandfathers have seen,' 10:6) — a hyperbolic scale that functions as a warning of inexorable escalation. When Pharaoh's own servants crack (10:7) — 'Do you not realize that Egypt is destroyed?' — the narrative signals that Pharaoh's pride has now become self-destructive folly visible even to his inner circle. He summons Moses and Aaron back (10:8), but immediately reaches for a compromise: only the men may go (10:11). The negotiation reveals the anatomy of partial obedience — Pharaoh is willing to worship if he can define the terms. Moses will not accept it. The expulsion of Moses and Aaron from the throne room (10:11) closes the negotiation with the eighth plague still pending."
